Recidivism Prediction in Broward County, FL

Xingxing Shu

1. Introduction

Preventing recidivism, the repeat incarceration of a previously released offender, is an opportunity to break the cycle of incarceration that affects hundreds of thousands of people in the US.Recidivism, or the repeat incarceration of an ex-offender, is a preventable problem. When an ex-offender re-offends, the community and the individual both suffer social and financial loss.In mid-2016, ProPublica published an analysis of a machine learning tool built by a company called Northpointe to assess the rehabilitation needs of Broward County, Florida inmates.A traditional solution, to expressly exclude race from the model, is insufficient because other variables, such as education, residence, and certain crime types, are strongly correlated with race and serve as race indicators in the model. In this project, I tried to understand the extent of racial bias and demonstrate accuracy & generalizability metrics by exploring the trade-off in model predictions between maximizing social benefits and maximizing fairness.

The original dataset contains 7,214 inmates with 53 variables, after selection, the new data includes 6,163 inmates in Broward County. Of those, 2,801 are listed as having a recidivism event. 51% of the inmates are African American and 81% are males.

3. Model Building

In this section I developed two predictive models, one with race and one without. You will do this in order to understand how the algorithm reacts to the inclusion of race as a control.

Given sample size limitations as evidenced by the plot, only African American, Caucasian and Hispanic were included in the models.

I controlled race (one model with and one without) and kept other variables same: sex, age, the number of other convictions as a juvenile, the count of prior adult convictions and the length of stay in prison. Then use createDataPartition to split the data into a 75% training set and a 25% test set. Use 100 fold cross-validation to train the models. For each test set permutation, I calculated three goodness of fit indicaters - the Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC), Sensitivity and Specificity.

set.seed(336)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(df$priors_count, p = .75,
                                    list = FALSE,
                                    times = 1)
train <- df[ trainIndex,]
test  <- df[-trainIndex,]
set.seed(125)
reg.noRace.cv <- train(Recidivated ~ ., data = train %>%
                                               select(-race,
                                               -r_charge_degree,
                                               -r_charge_desc,
                                               -c_charge_degree,
                                               -c_charge_desc,
                                               -two_year_recid),
 family="binomial"(link="logit"), method="glm", 
 metric="ROC",
 trControl = trainControl(method = "cv",number = 40,classProbs = TRUE, summaryFunction=twoClassSummary))

reg.withRace.cv <- train(Recidivated ~ ., data = train %>%
                                               select(
                                               -r_charge_degree,
                                               -r_charge_desc,
                                               -c_charge_degree,
                                               -c_charge_desc,
                                               -two_year_recid),
 family="binomial"(link="logit"), method="glm", 
 metric="ROC",
 trControl = trainControl(method = "cv",number = 40,classProbs = TRUE, summaryFunction=twoClassSummary))
testProbs <- 
  rbind(
    data.frame(class = test$two_year_recid,
               probs = predict(reg.noRace.cv, test, type="prob")$Recidivate,
               predClass = ifelse(predict(reg.noRace.cv, test, type="prob")$Recidivate > .5 ,1,0),
               regression = "No Race",
               Race = test$race),
    data.frame(class = test$two_year_recid,
               probs = predict(reg.withRace.cv, test, type="prob")$Recidivate,
               predClass = ifelse(predict(reg.withRace.cv, test, type="prob")$Recidivate > .5 ,1,0),
               regression = "With Race",
               Race=test$race))

4. Evaluating accuracy

The overall AUCs with and without race are both 0.77 which indicates the model without racial factor has nothing to do with the prediction. Therefore, race does not have a strong predictive power in an overall sense. To have a better view of the race factor, next we gonna check the accuracy by looking at the AUCs of the three major racial groups, Caucasians, African Americans, and Hispanics. Within each model, the AUCs show that the models predict the recidivism of African Americans the best, Hispanics the second, and Caucasians the third. Both models are almost equally accurate across racial groups.

5. Evaluating bias

In this section we analyze whether our models generalize well across different racial groups. We will use the model estimated above that does not have any race in it.

First, build a facetted barplot where the leftmost plot shows observed recidivism rates by race for African Americans, Whites and Hispanics. On the rightmost plot, show predictied recidivism rates by the same race groups. Interpret this plot with respect to race.

Next, we plot the confusion matrix for the three racial groups.

testProbs %>%
  filter(Race == "Caucasian" | Race == "African-American" | Race == "Hispanic") %>%
  filter(regression == "No Race") %>%
  group_by(Race) %>%
  summarize(Observed.Recidivism.Rate = sum(class) / n(),
            Predicted.Recidivism.Rate = sum(predClass) / n())%>%
  select(Race,Observed.Recidivism.Rate,Predicted.Recidivism.Rate)%>%
  gather(key="measure", value="value",c('Observed.Recidivism.Rate','Predicted.Recidivism.Rate'))%>%
    ggplot(.,aes(x=Race, y=value)) +
    geom_bar(aes(fill=Race),position="dodge",stat="identity") +
    facet_wrap(~measure) +
    scale_fill_manual(values = palette_3_colors) +
    labs(title="Observed & predicted recidivism rates ",
         subtitle = "Broward County - Source: Propublica",
         x="Race",y="Rate") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
    plotTheme()

testProbs %>%
  filter(Race == "Caucasian" | Race == "African-American" | Race == "Hispanic") %>%
  filter(regression == "No Race") %>%
  group_by(Race) %>%
  count(predClass,class) %>%
  summarize(sum_trueNeg = sum(n[predClass==0 & class==0]),
            sum_truePos = sum(n[predClass==1 & class==1]),
            sum_falseNeg = sum(n[predClass==0 & class==1]),
            sum_falsePos = sum(n[predClass==1 & class==0]),
            total=sum(n)) %>%
  mutate(True_Positive = sum_truePos / total,
         True_Negative = sum_trueNeg / total,
         False_Negative = sum_falseNeg / total,
         False_Positive = sum_falsePos / total,
         Accuracy = (sum_truePos + sum_trueNeg) / total) %>%
  select(Race, True_Positive, True_Negative, False_Negative, False_Positive,Accuracy) %>%
  gather(key,value,True_Positive:Accuracy) %>%
    ggplot(.,aes(reorder(key, value,FUN = max),value,fill=Race)) +
    geom_bar(aes(fill=Race),position="dodge",stat="identity") +
    scale_fill_manual(values = palette_3_colors) +
    labs(title="Confusion matrix rates by race (50% threshold)",
         subtitle = "Broward County - Source: Propublica",
         x="Outcome",y="Rate") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
    plotTheme()

The trade-off between accuracy and generalizability is that higher accuracy requires higher true negative and true positive rates, the latter favoring race. If you want to make sure that those who have the opportunity to participate in a vocational training program have very low recidivism rates, this algorithm gives more whites and Latins the opportunity than African-Americans. The reason may be that African Americans are being targeted by the police. Therefore, they are again likely to be arrested and sink. The model will always produce biased results unless this potential bias is ruled out. Therefore, this model is not recommended.

6. Generating costs and benefits

library(kableExtra)
reci_table <-
   testProbs %>%
      count(predClass, class) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predClass==0 & class==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predClass==1 & class==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predClass==0 & class==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predClass==1 & class==0])) %>%
       gather(Variable, Count)%>%
  mutate(Revenue =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative", Count * 10600,
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive",((10600 - 2000) * (Count * .50)) + (-86040 * (Count * .50)),
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", (-36000) * Count,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", (10600 - 2000) * Count, 0))))) %>%
    bind_cols(data.frame(Description = c(
              "We predicted no recidivism and there's no recidivism",
              "We predicted recidivism and there is recidivism",
              "We predicted no recidivism but there is recidivism",
              "We predicted recidivism but there's no recidivism")))

iterateThresholds <- function(data) {
  x = .01
  all_prediction <- data.frame()
  while (x <= 1) {
  
  this_prediction <-
      testProbs %>%
      mutate(predOutcome = ifelse(probs > x, 1, 0)) %>%
      count(predOutcome, class) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & class==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & class==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & class==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & class==0]),
            total=sum(n)) %>%
     gather(Variable, Count) %>%
     mutate(Revenue =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative", Count * 10600,
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive",((10600 - 2000) * (Count * .50)) + (-18600 * (Count * .50)),
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", (-36000) * Count,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", (10600 - 2000) * Count, 0)))),
            Threshold = x)
  
  all_prediction <- rbind(all_prediction, this_prediction)
  x <- x + .01
  }
return(all_prediction)
}
whichThreshold <- iterateThresholds(testProbs)

whichThreshold_revenue <- 
  whichThreshold %>% 
    mutate(actualChurn = ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive", (Count * .5),
                         ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", Count, 0))) %>% 
    group_by(Threshold) %>% 
    summarize(Revenue = sum(Revenue),
              Actual_Churn_Rate = sum(actualChurn) / sum(Count),
              Actual_Churn_Revenue =  sum(actualChurn * 10600),
              Revenue_Next_Period = Revenue - Actual_Churn_Revenue)

These cost/benefit functions are incredibly revealing. Its clear that Revenue keeps declining. The trend for Revenue_Next_Period is similar, but interestingly, the slope of the line is much steeper.

If everyone who is predicted to recidivate is enrolled in the program, we can calculate what the societal cost would be by adding up the costs of each of the four possible outcomes and multiplying them by the number of ex-offenders predicted to have that outcome. Since the number of ex-offenders who fall into each outcome varies by the threshold use, we can optimize our model by using the threshold which minimizes the overall cost of all four outcomes.

It is possible to create a recidivism risk score that predicts equally well for blacks and whites without including race as in the model. Additionally, we demonstrated that a cost/benefit equation can be derived to inform the threshold for predicting repeat offense. We hope that this work inspires other to build upon this proof of concept and develop transparent predictive algorithms that assess racial, or other, fairness.
